Joesph<br>
I can understand your wanting to know about your fathers war, as I remember wanting to know about my own fathers war. I grew up wanting to know about his abdominal scars and why he had no belly button, and it was only when I was too old to believe that, &quot;one day I got so hungry, that I ate it&quot;, that I embarked on a journey of years and years searching as he would never speak of the &quot;big&quot; one, nor did he spend time with other vets so that I could overhear the bravodo talk or stories over cameraderie. It was three years that I learned that he had taken seven rounds across the gut and lost a kidney and lord knows how many feet of intestines. It took me a couple more years to find the footlocker that had papers, pictures, a carton of Wing cigarettes, and his purple heart. And it took me even many more years to learn of his history, but of which none of the stories would he let go. All I got was second or third hand.<br><br>
But that is not why I write to you today. You wrote of wanting to do a tribute on the thirtieth. I am here to re-inform you that that day belongs to the people of South Vietnam, and the tribute should be directed to them. Not wanting to give history lessons, you might want to research what had happened after the fall of Saigon, the exodus of the Boat People, the situation of the Refugees and the camps spread from Thailand through Taiwan of which some still stand and house the same refugees of many years ago. You may also want to investigate the shabby, pitiful, and disgraceful support by the US and the Allies after the Fall of these same people as we no longer had a monetary investment in these people, there was very little concern that they were bait for the sharks and blood thirsty pirates of the International waters.  You may also use that day to remember the Cambodians and what was happening to the millions who were at the mercy of Pol Pot. I understand that you work with school kids, but I trust that you, as a teacher, can teach these things in a manner befitting their age, because if you don't, as with much of you fathers history, it will be swept under the rug, only to be forgotten.
